## Your Task
Analyze the repository structure above for the following architectural anti-patterns.
Focus on patterns that are ONLY visible at the repository level — do not flag individual file bugs.

### Anti-Patterns to Detect

**Feature Envy** (`Feature Envy`)
A module that repeatedly accesses data or behavior from other modules more than its own.
Look for: a file that imports many modules from a single foreign package and delegates most of its logic there.

**Anemic Domain Model** (`Anemic Domain Model`)
Domain/model files that contain only data fields with no behavior (business logic lives entirely in service files).
Look for: files named `model.*` or `entity.*` with no methods, while corresponding `service.*` files do all the work.

**Layer Violation** (`Layer Violation`)
A module in a higher layer directly importing from a module more than one rank below (skipping layers), or a lower layer importing from a higher one (upward dependency).

**Tight Coupling** (`Tight Coupling`)
A module that imports from many other modules across different subsystems, creating high fan-out and change sensitivity.

**Distributed Monolith** (`Distributed Monolith`)
The codebase is split into many packages/services but they all import each other directly with no clear API boundaries, combining the worst of both monolith and distributed architectures.

